{"name": "(Unstructured) Thoughts", "id": 209, "content": "<p>Social norms are like games. The rules of the gaame are &mdash;&nbsp;in the first phase &mdash;&nbsp;discovered/explored, then &mdash; in the second phase &mdash; they are made immutable. Take for example, the game of chess, the rules of chess are immutable, even if they might not make any sense.</p>\n\n<p>You could say, no they are not immutable. Well, they are for the players of the <em><strong>chess.&nbsp;</strong></em>Now, it is quite possible that some person(s) don&#39;t find the rules of chess sensible, and they modify the rules, and in process they invent a new game, and after some exploration, that new game has immutable rules. This process is perhaps a good summary of what has been going on in terms of social norms.</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p>Isn&#39;t it interesting that, for example, on a guitar every song is available. But not all musicians can discover any song by their will. What they discover is reflective of their experience.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Even if a super-duper-computer discovers all possibilities, would it have any significance.</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p>Road to unconscious goes from the territory of conscious activities. E.g. in learning any skill.</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p>Magic disappears when it is observed. Thoughts, passions, etc are all like magic.</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p>Language is not taaught to the child, the child just needs to be exposed to linguistic setup. It has been seen that deaf children, with interaction among just a few other children picks up the sign language. - Chomsky</p>\n\n<p>If a person develops language by interactions, and since every other entity in the world is just another entity, and the person doesn&#39;t have access to the inner world of the entity, then does it really have to be that the entity is conscious. Isn&#39;t there a segment of language that deals with non-conscious entities, doesn&#39;t it have a language to interact with the systems like nature.</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p>It&#3