e products of the body interacting&nbsp;with the environment along with the complex internal processing of thoughts, experiences and memory.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p class=\"mentions-texteditor__content\">The body can be controlled, hence we can use the body to control emotions as well. The mind also can be used to command the processing of the mind itself, the body and as well as the emotions. All this can be explored through Yoga and Meditation.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p class=\"mentions-texteditor__content\">Anything that you do has two aspects: One aspect is that you are doing it to <em>escape</em> what you are, what life is - the emptiness. The other aspect is to <em>enhance</em> yourself, enhance life.</p>\n\n<p class=\"mentions-texteditor__content\">You are in a circle anyway whether you are enhancing or escaping at a point of time. The circle is caused by thought, desire.</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p class=\"mentions-texteditor__content\">For transferring knowledge to a person, or rather help a person discover some knowledge, we first need to understand the person himself. How does he perceive things, can he focus on abstractions, or is he just able to focus on concrete. Can he swim across an unfamiliar territory, or does he need a guided field with some final objective (e.g. in that we should start from the current state of our knowledge about reality, and then teach him how we arrived here). What kind of analogies does he need (because analogies are the foundation of understanding)..</p>\n\n<p class=\"mentions-texteditor__content\">But the main problem is dichotomization. First, it&#39;s not easy, second it will never be accurate, since people can change also. However, the range of possible change is limited. How do we find that?</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p class=\"mentions-texteditor__content\">If a person treats some (selected) people in a very nice way, but not others. Does it make him/her a good person? Not for me. A person will always treat some in a nice way, as necessitated by social games.</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p class=\"mentions-texteditor__content\">Why is it that some people are more moved by one facet of the idea, but not the other? E.g. for the idea of stealing for example, there is also the idea of non-stealing. Then why does a person just stick to the first one, why is he under the influence of it? - Because it is his habit. Of course the reason given is the benefit that it brings about, which in turn is for bringing happiness. But that sort of happiness is itself just an idea, why not the other ideas of happiness? There is an idea that happiness is in non-stealing, doing good etc...</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p class=\"mentions-texteditor__content\">Same problems&nbsp;different solutions &mdash; Everything fades away, each object of pleasure becomes non-pleasant. Even love fades away.</p>\n\n<p class=\"mentions-texteditor__content\">Indian philosophers&#39;&nbsp;solution:&nbsp;when everything, even love, fails, that,&nbsp;man finds out&nbsp;how vain, how dream-like is this world. Renunciate this world, and seek what&#39;s beyond, or beneath, all this.</p>\n\n<p class=\"mentions-texteditor__content\">Others&#39;&nbsp;solution: one object of pleasure has stopped being pleasant? Find another object that is pleasant. Love faded away? Find someone new to love. Simple. Repeat till you die.</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p class=\"mentions-texteditor__content\">Matter is the &ldquo;permanent possibility of sensation,&rdquo; said John Stuart Mill.</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p class=\"mentions-texteditor__content\">Does gravity exist if there are no bodies containing mass? - If not, then do objects &quot;create&quot; the force of gravity?</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p class=\"mentions-texteditor__content\">If a person decides not to participate in the games which apparently humans involve themselves in, in order to keep themselves busy, what remains there to do? What happens when you don&#39;t &quot;want&quot; and &quot;need&quot; anything other than food, and you are getting that?</p>\n\n<p cla