 stupid as well. They don&#39;t consider the brute fact that even though they worked hard, had skills etc, still chance is such a strong element....&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>What are they really proud of? That they achieved something, accomplished something? If you do something, and it turns out to be well, it&#39;s not that you did well. You just did something, as per your capabilities, and the result turned out to be what it did. And if you are proud of the fact that you did your best, then the outcome doesn&#39;t matter anyway. I must assume that those who are proud in the second way, are respectable, humble and huamanistic. Those who are proud in the first way are beasts.</p>\n\n<p>See it like this, for a seed to grow into a plant or a tree many things are required - seed itself, sunlight, soil, minerals, water, shade etc.. If you created each one of these by your virtue, then you can say that you are solely responsible for success (as outcome). Just keep this in mind, that all things are necessary. Also, that if you do not have seed, you will definitely not have the tree or the plant.</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p>I have the free will to do anything, but I don&#39;t have the will to will anything. My will itself is a function of a lot of things which are not consciously chosen.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>If there are 20% doing wrong, then there are 90% allowing it consciously, subconsciously, or unconsciously.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Who are you friends with, what are you friends with, where are you friends with, why?&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>What is the first requirement for critical thinking.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;- That you must be fully aware that your intuitions and more importantly your logical arguments might be wrong.</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J5wuB_p63YM\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=J5wuB_p63YM (Chomsky vs Foucault)</a></p>\n\n<p>Chomsky: A fundamental element of human nature is creative work, free creation wihout any suppression, oppression, coercion, destruction etc. <em>[Is it so? How many humans are seen engaging in creative work?]</em></p>\n\n<p>Anarcho-Syndicalism : A federated, decentralized system of free association incorporating social as well as economic institutions. suppression, oppression, coercion, destruction which exist now only as historical residue will be eliminated. It is an appropriate form of social organization for an advanced technological society.</p>\n\n<p>Foucault:</p>\n\n<p>People know only about direct exertion of political power by govt e.g. police, army; there are other indirect institutions (which seem neutral and independent) which are used e.g. universities (education system in general), psychiatry, justice which exclude instruments of power of certain social class. We first need to criticize this mode of working, then move to formula future of society, otherwise these forms would reproduce themselves even in ideal organizations like Anarcho-Syndicalism.</p>\n\n<p>Chomsky: agree... also financial institutions e.g. MNCs appear to be neutral but are form of oppression, coercion. This is definitely a task of intellectual community. But also, we can&#39;t throw the abstract concepts of a just society should be, we should know what it would look like in future (even if we don&#39;t know the details).</p>\n\n<p>Foucault: Isn&#39;t there a danger there? These human natures you are talking about which have not been realized so far and so on, don&#39;t we risk defining this human nature in terms borrowed from out society, our culture, civilization? E.g. Marxism asserted that human nature was alienated in a capitalist system, and Marxism ultimately dreamed of a liberated human nature. On the other hand what model did Marxism use to conceive, project and eventually realize that human nature? It was in fact, the Bourgeois model. And this happened in Soviet Union. A utopic and real kind of society had been reconstituted. Look what happened. It&#39;s difficult to conceive what human nature is.</p>\n\n<p>Chomsky: Acknowledge that. But just like in political situations it seems urgency to take some action even if there is danger in taking it like in case of Civial Disobedience (an action undertaken under lot of uncertainities about its effect like it threatens the social order in ways which might bring on Fascism) but at the same time there was great danger in not undertaking an action (society of Indo-China will be shred under the power of America). Similarly in intellectual domain even though there are uncertainities, we need to take some action.</p>\n\n<p>Foucault:</p>\n\n<p>The notion of Justice itself functions within a society of classes as a claim made by and as a justification for the class which is oppressed. In a classless society, I&#39;m not sure we would still be using this notion of justice.</p>\n\n<p>Chomsky: Disagree. There is some sort of absolute basis ultimately residing in fundamental human qualities in terms of which our real notion of justice is grounded. Even though our existing systems of justice embody systems of class oppression, and other kinds of oppression, it&#39;s too hasty to characterize them as mere justification of oppression.</p>\n\n<p>My main takeaway from this talk: Philosophers (try to) see something that is not obvious (although it could be just a figment of mind?).</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p>We are buying more and more time using technology. But do we know what to do with that time? What will you do with all the time in future?</p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>Hang out with your family, friends? - The more time you have, more boring it will become <em>(specially in combination with below points)</em> <em>[Is it a controversial statement?]</em>.</li>\n\t<li>Travel? - But the side-effect of technology is that you will see more and more similarity and less and less nature (and wonder) in environments at different places <em>(I can see natural places getting &quot;transformed&quot; into &quot;modern world&quot;, so why not?)</em