nderstand, the problem is those who misunderstand <em>(and think that they have understood it well).</em></p>\n\n<hr />\n<p>Less emotional connection with things/people =&gt; Realization of Emptiness</p>\n\n<p>OR Realization of Emptiness =&gt; Less emotional connection with things/people.</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p>Some are saying that AI is trying to do face recognition and associated things with million examples, however, we as humans have gained memory and circuitry through evolution using billions and trillions of examples.</p>\n\n<p>Now everyone has this capability. It seems that all these examples could not come from one single pair of eyes (i.e. One person). Somehow the data (examples) collected by multiple people gathered and installed in everyone?</p>\n\n<p>Is it transferred by genes?</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p>The rule for getting your blog famous:</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; Have an interesting thing to say, say it in an interesting way. Do this for many years, and you are done.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp; (advertisements, growth hacks also play a role).</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p lang=\"en-US\">Don&#39;t try to be happy when you have mixed feelings or negative feelings, it will create something complex and negative reducing the effect of happiness. Just relax, focus on normal breath, and watch the feeling.</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p lang=\"en-US\">My Skepticism for Buddhism:</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">How can one person gain so much knowledge (which is even supported by modern psychology at least on a high level) just sitting under the tree?</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">But we can clearly ignore the claim that Buddha&#39;s teaching was written by many people, as people like to gain a reputation for the work they do.&nbsp;Also, if multiple people were involved, there is a high chance that it would have been apparent somehow. (maybe I need to research more)</p>\n\n<p>Rebirth - We do not have many examples of this happening, Buddhism arose from Hinduism, and somehow this concept was already there for a long time. Dalai Lama selection is done by testing reincarnation. If rebirth is not true, then a lot of things in Buddhism would be falsified.</p>\n\n<p>If somehow it gets proven that there is no rebirth, what&#39;s the USP of Buddhism? Isn&#39;t it pity that so many people <em>wasted</em>&nbsp;their lives in pursuit of freedom from the cycle of birth-rebirth (which never even existed)? OTOH, did they have any life <em>(a conventional life that would fit into normal society)</em> in the first place, because if they had such life, it would have found its way and they would not have turned monks?</p>\n\n<p>Ok, but even if they had no life, the waste a potential life.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p class=\"mentions-texteditor__content\">One of the arguments for the theory of reincarnation is this: Many times it has been seen where ducks have been hatched by hens, that, as soon as they come out of the eggs, they flew to water, and the mother thought they would be drowned. If experience be the only source of knowledge, where did these chickens learn to pick up food, or the ducklings that the water was their natural element? If you say it is instinct, it means nothing&mdash;it is simply giving it a word, but is no explanation. What is this instinct? We have many instincts in ourselves. For instance, most of you ladies play the piano, and remember, when you first learned, how carefully you had to put your fingers on the black and the white keys, one after the other, but now, after long years of practice, you can talk with your friends, and your hand goes on just the same. It has become instinct, it becomes automatic, but so far as we know, all the cases which we now regard as automatic are degenerated reason.</p>\n\n<p class=\"mentions-texteditor__content\">In the language of the Yogi, instinct is involved reason. Discrimination becomes involved, and gets to be automatic Samskaras. Therefore it is perfectly logical to think that all we call instinct in this world is simply involved reason. As reason cannot come without experience, all instinct is, therefore, the result of past experience. Chickens fear the hawk, and ducklings love the water, and these are both the result of past experience, and these are both the result of past experience. Then the question is whether that experience belongs to a particular soul, or to the body simply, whether this experience which comes to the duck is the duck&rsquo;s forefather&rsquo;s experience, or the duck&rsquo;s own experience. Modern scientific menhold that it belongs to the body, but the Yogis hold that it is the experience of the soul, transmitted through the body. This is called the theory of reincarnation. We have seen that all of our knowledge, whether we call it perception or reason, or instinct, must come through that one channel called experience, and all that we know call instinct is the result of past experience, degenerated into instinct, and that instinct regenerates into reason again. So on throughout the universe, and upon this has been built one of the chief arguments for reincarnation, in India.</p>\n\n<p class=\"mentions-texteditor__content\">One more skepticism about these &quot;enlightened&quot; people is: why are they in such a necessity to impart wisdom, to help others? It&#39;s ok for others that they do, but this necessity, compulsion is doubtful.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p lang=\"en-US\">Sigmund Freud books: The Interpretation of Dreams, The Ego and the Id</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p lang=\"en-US\">Okay, I get it, that all the ideas of not-self, higher consciousness may be derived due to our learnings (what we hear, what we see, what we imagine combined), from thoughts themselves, but the fact that it occurred for the first time means it either originated from pure imagination, or they saw the truth?</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">But what if you consider that imagination is not pure? (Imagination also is a function)</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">How did this sense of higher consciousness occur for the first first time? Was it <em>realization</em>, was it an effect of some drug/plant?</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p lang=\"en-US\">5 aggregates of self: Form, Feelings, Perception, Mental Formations, Consciousness</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; If I remove one(/some) of them, does it make sense if I say that I am not the same as I was, and hence I have got rid of that person.</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p lang=\"en-US\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;There is no magic in being happy. I can be happy without reason, just by thinking <em>(it&#39;s easy, all you need is a calm and clear mind)</em>, but sustaining that happiness and securing that happiness, is a challenge.</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In fact, anybody can become happy anytime. But we ordinary mortals need props to sustain and secure that happiness.</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p lang=\"en-US\">&nbsp;&nbsp;We like to think that humans are special. But in a normal flow of life, there is nothing special about an average human. An average human is just reacting to the environment forced by nature and nurture. Nature and nurture constantly play a dual; and habit, passion, attitude come out as the result of this dual. Nature and nurture affect psychology and physiology. Physiology and psychology also affect each other. An average human is not so special compared to an average animal. An average human is just another animal with a wider range of senses and brain cells, resulting&nbsp;in a somewhat wider spectrum of consciousness. But even with all the senses and consciousness, an average human lives unconsciously, just reacting to the environment forced by nature and nurture. An average human likes to think that (s)he has control, but fails to recognize that the control is just an illusion. The universe is a multi-variable system, an average human tries to control one/few variables, and correlates it with the outcome and control,&nbsp; but fails to see that the result is a combined effect of all the variables in the system. An average human thinks that (s)he has some identity, but fails to recognize that the very identity is an illusion which has been imprinted on his/her mind. An average human is nothing but a bit of consciousness bundled with nature(comprised of genetic materials), nurture(comprised of the pre-natal/natal/post-natal environment).</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This limited consciousness bundled with forces of nature and nurture results in psychological and physiological identity,</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Like, Dislike, Emotions (Anger, Calm, Affection, etc) all result from this bundle. The interesting thing is that this&nbsp;is not very different in animals.</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; An average human feels affection/love, anger, in very much the same way as other animals.</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; An average human thinks that there is a soulmate for everyone, what they fail to recognize that all the traits in their solumate are not something special, they are just complicated reactions of many forces working together.</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">But there is one thing that makes humans special: the ability to think so much, and the control resulting from training&nbsp;of the mind, the ability to break this chain of nature and nurture <em>(but even this breakage might be an illusion)</em>.</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p lang=\"en-US\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; There&#39;s so much debate about Consciousness and Intelligence. Some say that it&#39;s something special, some say that it&#39;s just information processing and reaction; that we can reduce it to logic.</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; I find it very analogous to romantic love. For lovers, it is something special that they feel towards each other.</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; While onlookers can easily tell that it&#39;s just about compatibility match on an emotional, psychological level.</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Can anybody prove that love is just an emotional game and not something special?</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Well, you can; but it won&#39;t matter for the lovers, they will continue feeling special and onlookers will doubt occasionally that &quot;Are we missing something?&quot;</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">&nbsp; &nbsp; The same thing goes with Consciousness and Intelligence, you can reduce it to logic and enact it in AI toys, but it seems that there will always be &quot;something more&quot; which cannot be captured in logic and algorithms.</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p lang=\"en-US\">As long as you are revelling in the high tides of energy, like enjoying overpowering, lust, anger, or are under the influence of substances; you have no problem.</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The problem occurs when you come down from these high tides. And it can happen anytime, for any reason (including external factors, and self-realisation; yes mind is mysterious, it can turn anytime).</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; That&#39;s the time when satisfaction arising from virtues come into play. That&#39;s when the soul matters. That&#39;s when altruism, compassion, serenity, spirituality, enlightenment etc matter.</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">&nbsp; Why be good? So that your soul helps you in these times.</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p lang=\"en-US\">&nbsp;&nbsp; Why did we develop fear as our defence mechanism? Why did the meditative and attentive mind did not develop as a result of evolution?</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p lang=\"en-US\">&nbsp;If I imagine a certain situation&nbsp;and enjoy it without forming some kind of expectation, that can still be enjoyable, after all, you enjoy dreams as much as real events; until you realize that they are not true. But if I imagine and form expectations, that will lead to suffering.</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p lang=\"en-US\">Suppose we catch a criminal who has murdered someone. We catch him/her, and wipe out their memory. Then we punish them by some mental pain and show them their history what they had done. Are we really punishing a criminal? (thought of this while watching Black Mirror: White Bear)</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p lang=\"en-US\">What is good and what is bad, what is beautiful and what is ugly, what ought to be and what ought not to be, are all determined by what each one of us feels.</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">When two people agree on this they make friends/family, when many agree they form a community, when they want to separate themselves from others they form a country.</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">They continuously try to convince themselves and others that what they feel is correct.</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p lang=\"en-US\">WD Snodgrass: Valediction (poem):</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Political people, they have learned a long time ago that if they want to take you captive, the best way to do that is</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; to tell you that &quot;someone else has taken you captive and they know how you can be free&quot;, they will set you free,</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; all you have to do is exactly what they tell you from now on, and this is the kind of thing that lovers do also</p>\n\n<p lang=\"en-US\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; it works for both of those rascals.</p>\n\n<hr />\n<p lang=\"en-US\"><strong>TODO:&nbsp; Artificial Evolution</strong> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://samharris.org/\">https://samharris.org/</a></p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.pnas.org/search/\">http://www.pnas.org/search/</a> (Psychological researches)</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://arxiv.org/\">https://arxiv.org/</a> (Research papers)</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://brucelipton.com/\">http://brucelipton.com/</a></p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NNnIGh9g6fA&amp;t=115s\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NNnIGh9g6fA&amp;t=115s</a></p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://www.peerlyst.com/posts/how-to-prepare-for-the-oscp-a-study-plan-magda-chelly-ph-d\">https://www.peerlyst.com/posts/how-to-prepare-for-the-oscp-a-